In 1993, [[Jake and Dinos Chapman]] of the [[Young British Artists]] movement created 82 miniature, toy-like sculptures modelled on ''The Disasters of War''. The works were widely acclaimed and were purchased that year by the [[Tate]] gallery.<ref>[http://www.tate.org.uk/servlet/ViewWork?cgroupid=999999961&workid=26398&searchid=12001 Disasters of War  1993]. [[Tate]]. Retrieved 29 August, 2009.</ref> In 2003, the Chapman brothers exhibited an altered version of ''The Disasters of War''. They purchased a complete set of prints,<ref name = "Jones 2003"/><ref group=a>An edition that had been published in 1937, as a protest against [[Spanish Civil War#Atrocities|fascist atrocities]] in the [[Spanish Civil War]]</ref> over which they drew and pasted demonic clown and puppy heads.<ref>Jake and Dinos Chapman. "[http://www.artnet.com/magazine/reviews/laplaca/Images/laplaca7-21-12.jpg Insult to Injury]". artnet.com, 9 March, 2004. Retrieved 30 August, 2009.</ref> The Chapmans described their "rectified" images as making a connection between Napoleon's supposed introduction of [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] ideals to early-19th-century Spain and [[Tony Blair]] and [[George W. Bush]] purporting to [[Rationale for the Iraq War#Bringing democracy to the Middle East|bring democracy to Iraq]].<ref>Gibbons, Fiachra. "[http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2003/mar/31/arts.turnerprize2003 Chapman brothers 'rectify' Disasters of War. Art's enfants terribles pay tribute to Goya]". ''The Guardian'', 31 March, 2003. Retrieved  29 August, 2009.</ref>
{{clear}}

