|Plate 46: ''Esto es malo'' (''This is bad''). A monk is killed by French soldiers looting church treasures. A rare sympathetic image of a clergy generally shown on the side of oppression and injustice<ref name="Barnes" />
|Goya-Guerra (47).jpg|As the priests lay dead, soldiers make off with a large load of stolen church plate|Plate 47: ''As<U+00ED> sucedi<U+00F3>'' (''This is how it happened''). The last print in the first group. Murdered monks lay by French soldiers loot church treasures<ref name="Barnes"/> 
|Goya-Guerra (64).jpg|A cart is being loaded with the dead. A man hoists the body of a woman into the arms of a third man standing in the cart, while two other men carry more bodies to the cart to be loaded.|Plate 64: ''Carretadas al cementerio'' (''Cartloads for the cemetery''). The last print in the famine group
|Goya-Guerra (65).jpg|An official writes a report into a notebook as a woman in a white nightgown nearly swoons with her head in her hands, a man next to her holds his head in his hands expressing both fear and grief and a dog at his feet growls and threatens|Plate 65: ''Qu<U+00E9> alboroto es este?'' (''What is this hubbub?''). The first print in the final group. The woman likely represents the rejected Constitution of 1814<ref name="b59"/>
|Goya-Guerra (77).jpg|A cleric walks a tightrope (that is on the verge of breaking.) across the town plaza and over the heads of the people down below.|Plate 77: ''Que se rompe la cuerda!'' (''May the rope break!''). In the preparatory drawing the cleric was a Pope
|Goya-Guerra (78).jpg|Surrounded by wild wolves, a horse kicks and bucks defending its freedom and its life. A group of wolf hounds look on passively|Plate 78: ''Se defiende bien'' (''He defends himself well''). The horse appears to be a metaphor for the constitutional monarchy, fighting without help from the wolf-hounds, who perhaps represent anti-monarchical revolution<ref>Wilson-Bareau, 59. This is one of the prints apparently drawing from Giovanni Battista Casti</ref>
}}
